{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011RuX3GXYz1EDtgwHNKYtUs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the complete picture of all the changes made across stages:\n\n**Stage 01**: deploy_cluster with worker_replicas=2\n- Deployed ray-head (1 replica), ray-worker (2 replicas), ray-head-service (only gcs:6379)\n- Initial image: need to check, but the agent in stage_03 set image to 2.9.0 (both already showed 2.9.0 after the set)\n\nWait, in stage_03's agent.log output I can see:\n- The agent ran `kubectl -n ray set image deploy/ray-head ray-head=rayproject/ray:2.9.0 && kubectl -n ray set image deploy/ray-worker ray-worker=rayproject/ray:2.9.0`\n- The command produced no output, then the subsequent check showed the images were already at 2.9.0\n\nThis is interesting—the workflow parameter specified `from_image: 2.8.0`, but the cluster was already running 2.9.0 because the deploy_cluster resource files had that version baked in. So the set image command ran against images that were already at the target version.\n\nNow I need to understand what happened during the rollback in stage_01, which used the deploy_cluster resource with its own image specifications. the cluster was deployed with 2.9.0 in stage_01. In stage_03, the agent ran `kubectl set image` but there's no output captured, which could mean the image was already 2.9.0 (no change needed) or the command executed without logging the result. The kubectl_log.jsonl shows only GET requests initially, then the set image command, but since it was issued via Bash rather than through the kubectl proxy tunnel, it might not be fully recorded there. The baseline image should be 2.8.0 based on the workflow parameters, so the rollback needs to revert to that version. I should check what the oracle expects for this test to confirm the correct baseline values.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"in